grew by approximately 25% last year
February 8, 2005
BUCHAREST, Romania
The average production of genetically-modified (GM) soy grew by 50 tonnes to 250 tonnes per square kilometre last year, said Constantin Sin from the Romanian Ministry of Agriculture.
Soy is the only GM crop allowed in Romania for commercial purposes.
Additionally, the area cultivated with the modified soy increased from 396 km² in 2003 to 581 km² in 2004.
GM soy is mainly farmed in southeastern Romania, in the counties of Brăila, Călăraşi and Ialomiţa.
